.Dd May 11, 2026
.Dt NOBODY-SANDBOX 7
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm nobody-sandbox
.Nd sandbox backend behavior for nobody
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Xr nobody 1
prepares a sandbox before spawning the requested command.
The selected backend is recorded in the trace as
.Va sandbox.prepared .
.Pp
The current sandbox boundary is filesystem-focused.
Process policy and environment filtering happen in the runtime before spawn.
Network, MCP, browser, and secret enforcement are not sandboxed yet.
.Sh LINUX LANDLOCK
On Linux,
.Nm
uses Landlock as the default filesystem backend.
The runtime resolves policy paths relative to the current working directory,
adds read and write grants, and installs the Landlock rules in the child after
fork and before exec.
The parent runtime remains outside the child sandbox so it can write trace
events and supervise the process.
.Pp
The backend requires fully enforced Landlock ABI v3 filesystem rights.
If the kernel or host configuration reports partial enforcement, no
enforcement, or no Landlock support, the run fails.
.Pp
Read support paths are added for command startup and dynamic linking.
The backend derives paths from
.Ev PATH
and common system locations such as
.Pa /bin ,
.Pa /usr ,
.Pa /lib ,
and selected device files.
Policy read/write grants are still the application-specific boundary.
.Sh PATH RULES
.Va fs.read
and
.Va fs.write
entries must resolve to existing paths on Linux.
Relative paths are resolved from the working directory.
.Pa ~/
paths are expanded with
.Ev HOME .
.Pp
.Va fs.deny
entries are normalized for carve-out checks.
Landlock is allowlist-based and cannot express
.Qq deny this child path below an allowed parent .
For example, this policy can be simulated:
.Bd -literal
[fs]
read = ["."]
deny = [".env"]
.Ed
.Pp
but it cannot be faithfully enforced by Landlock because
.Pa .env
sits under the granted current-directory tree.
On Linux,
.Xr nobody 1
fails closed with a
.Qq cannot enforce fs.deny
diagnostic.
Grant narrower paths instead.
.Sh NON-LINUX HOSTS
On macOS and other non-Linux platforms, the current backend is
.Qq noop .
It records
.Va enforced=false
and prints a warning:
.Bd -literal
nobody: WARNING: Landlock filesystem enforcement is only available on Linux; filesystem policy is diagnostic only
.Ed
.Pp
The command still runs after process policy and environment filtering have
succeeded.
.Sh LIMITATIONS
The current sandbox does not provide:
.Bl -bullet -compact
.It
network egress enforcement;
.It
seccomp or namespace isolation;
.It
macOS sandbox profiles;
.It
MCP/tool-call mediation;
.It
browser-control mediation;
.It
secret-broker mediation.
.El
.Sh TRACE
The
.Va sandbox.prepared
event records:
.Bl -tag -width "enforced" -compact
.It Va backend
Backend name, such as
.Qq landlock
or
.Qq noop .
.It Va enforced
Boolean enforcement status.
.It Va warning
Backend warning, if any.
.El
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr nobody 1 ,
.Xr nobody-trace 5 ,
.Xr nobody.toml 5 ,
.Xr nobody-policy 7
